observations.recommendation:
We recommended, and Management through the City Accountant, agreed to implement the following actions:
Provide Allowance for Impairment on RPT Receivables amounting to ₱9.763 million which have been outstanding for more than five years by a debit to Deferred RPT Income and credit Allowance for Impairment - RPT Receivables;
Reclassify the SL for SET Receivables based on its taxable year and its corresponding collections to align with the GF recording of RPT Receivable for uniformity. Additionally, prepare aging of SET Receivables and provide appropriate Allowance for Impairment on SET Receivable aged more than five years by a debit to Deferred SET Income and credit to Allowance for Impairment - SET Receivables;
Regularly prepare an Ageing of RPT/SET Receivables and update the Allowance for Impairment for RPT/SET Receivables aged beyond five years at year end; and
Draw a JEV to make an adjusting entry to correct the balance of RPT Receivable amounting to ₱443,639.71.

We revised and reiterated our recommendations, and Management agreed to avail of the one-time cleansing as prescribed by COA Circular 2020-006 and require the:
Inventory Committee to conduct the annual physical count of PPE and its assessment for impairment, and to submit the RPCPPE to the Auditor not later than January 31 of each year;
Inventory Committee, the CGSO and the City Accountant to reconcile the RPCPPE with the property and accounting records as of December 31, 2021 and update it to the December 31, 2023 balances;
City Accountant to reclassify the mentioned PPE items and review the rest of the PPE accounts for possible misclassification, and make the necessary adjusting journal entries;
City Accountant to derecognize from the books the properties already turned over to other agencies and non-existing PPE items supported by proper documents; and
City Budget Office to allocate funds for payments of overtime and other logistical support to the Inventory Committee necessary to complete the physical count and reconciliation of records.

2.7   We recommended the following:
a. The Inventory Committee to prepare the RPCPPE according to the account classification as recorded by Accounting Department;
b. The Inventory Committee and the Accounting Staff assigned in the PPE record to reconcile the RPCPPE with the accounting records as of December 31, 2021;
c. The City Engineer to coordinate with the Segabi Engineering District, DPWH on the projects of the City Government being taken over by that office and validate whether the completed projects by the DPWH will be turned over to the City Government.  If not, secure documentary evidence to that effect and make the necessary report to the City Accountant;
d. The City Accountant to make the necessary adjustment on its books of accounts on the remaining carrying value of the six (6) road network being removed due to its replacement/renovation by the DPWH;
e. The Inventory Committee to determine the replacement cost of the 19 road network that has no existing cost and make the necessary report to the City Accountant;
f. The City Accountant to recognize the cost of the nineteen (19) road network as provided for under COA Circular No. 2020-006; and
g. The City Accountant to derecognize the cost of various animals under the animal dispersal program.

3.9  We recommended that Management should require the:
The CTO in coordination with the City Budget Office to formulate its internal policy requiring the submission of obligation request at year-end for proper accounting;
b.   City Accountant to:
1.   Properly accrue all unpaid obligations on the year it was incurred;
2.  Observe proper cut-off; and
3.  Avoid the improper use of PPA account.

5.19  We recommended that Management:
a.   Direct the City Treasurer to:
1. Unload the Cashier III of either her collecting or disbursing function, whichever is appropriate;
2. Not grant any cash advance to a designated Liquidating Officer to avoid incompatible functions;
Discontinue and/or stop the designation of personnel from the Office of the City Accountant as SDO to ensure check and balance; and
Ensure that there are no existing cases of incompatible functions particularly for collections and disbursement.

11.8  We recommended that the:
a)  City Engineer and the City Planning and Development Coordinator to integrate the CSHP in the computation of construction costs of all projects to be implemented by the City, whether by contract of by Administration to ensure the protection and welfare of the workers at the construction site;
b)  Bids and Awards Committee to require interested Contractors to submit DOLE-approved CSHP for projects undertaken by contract.

Management require the GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) to:
a. Attend seminars of GAD particularly members of the Focal Point System;
b. Institutionalize the GAD database with adequate and systematically gathered sex-disaggregated data which will provide the bases for gender analysis, planning, programming and policy formation;
c. Undertake gender analysis to identify and confirm existing gender issues and ensure that the programs, projects and activities are responsive to the said issues; and
d. Revisit Annex B of Philippine Commission on Women (PCW)-DILG-DBM-National Economic and Development Authority (NEDA) JMC No. 2013-01, which identifies the data requirements for particular gender issues.

We recommended that Management require:

 The City Accountant to reclassify the 28 real estate to its appropriate account classification based on the purpose and actual usage during acquisition; 

 To create a taskforce that will focus in the production/retrieval of necessary documents for the eventual titling in the name of the LGU; and

 The coordination of the taskforce with the Land Registration Authority (LRA) to verify whether said real properties were already transferred in the name of the LGU or otherwise;

Initiate the titling of the parcels of the land purchased by the LGU to establish legal and true ownership of the real estate; 

Require the City Treasurer, City Accountant and CGSO to maintain and keep on file complete records of the City’s real properties; and

We recommended that Management to:

Direct the Market Committee to aggressively enforce/impose fees/ charges to violators and intensify collections;

Maintain accurate records of lease holders for proper accounting and assessment;

Have a random physical inspection of the units noting its movement/turnover;

Implement the yearly renewal of lease contracts; and

Have a sound monitoring and control mechanism to safeguard the interest of the LGU.

The City Accountant must:

Furnish the Department Heads and Division Chiefs a list of long-outstanding unliquidated cash advances of employees under their charge, including SDOs;

Send out demand letters for the immediate refund and/or liquidation of cash advances;

Abide by the provision of COA Circular No. 97-002 to ensure proper granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances, including the withholding of salaries of accountable officers who fail to render or settle unliquidated accounts within the prescribed period.

Institute appropriate legal sanction against employees concerned by withholding or suspension of their salaries under Article 218 of the Revised Penal Code or criminal prosecution under Section 128, PD 1445.
